          "body": "Jacob wakes with two confessions: *the LORD is in this place, and I did not know it* (28:16) — admission of spiritual blindness — and *this is none other than the house of God, and this is the gate of heaven* (28:17). He turns the stone he used as a headrest into a *matstsevah* (pillar), anoints it with oil (the chapter's only explicit act of consecration), renames the city Bethel ('house of God'), and vows. The vow is theologically awkward: God has just *unconditionally* promised everything Jacob now asks for conditionally — *if God will be with me, will keep me, will give me food and clothing, and bring me back, then Yahweh will be my God* (28:20-22). Jacob is still negotiating. The chapter ends not with Jacob transformed but with Jacob beginning a twenty-year journey in which the God of Bethel will hold him to this vow (31:13; 35:1-7)."
